elements.2211.03212_d7de4fe5e9a9be5469117790ffe65: Quantum computers can outperform classical computers in certain tasks
elements.2211.03212_2252a8e75115157eefcaf7ff17e08: However, there are still many challenges to the current quantum computers such as decoherence and fault tolerance, and other drawbacks such as portability and accessibility
elements.2211.03212_e29bab6eae7adee1596ad41c563ac: In this study, we circumvent these issues by realizing an analog quantum emulation device (AQED) where each qubit state is represented by a unique analog signal
elements.2211.03212_800fe089d04f330a93ecf44f328b6: It is possible to do this because previously it was shown that Hermitian operations on a Hilbert space are not unique to quantum systems and can also be applied to a basis of complex signals that form a Hilbert space
elements.2211.03212_652515a4fc04d83ae0fb83f2e1749: Orthogonality of the complex signal basis can be maintained by separating the signals into the frequency domain or the spatial domain
elements.2211.03212_ae0b5072851bae73aebb753d6b60d: We study both these approaches and present a comparison
elements.2211.03212_0bb83586ef92559554a84662c8178: We finally realize the entire device on a UMC 180nm processing node and demonstrate the computational advantage of an AQED by emulating Grover's search algorithm (GSA) and Quantum Fourier Transform (QFT)
elements.2211.03212_6460e635cfe009169cd7cacf6019d: We also present the equivalent quantum volume achieved by this device.
elements.2211.03212_b9ac72cfc3efbd1f85083a8c32a7d: Grover's Search Algorithm, Quantum Fourier Transform, Quantum Emulation Device
elements.2211.03212_3d03426c940f35cac1f6a35b5dbdf: A quantum computer provides a new computational paradigm that is fundamentally different from a classical computer
elements.2211.03212_934a2e8d8403f607334f084ce0146: This revolutionary idea reconciles the theory of computation with quantum physics and has shown great promise in solving a broad variety of problems that are originally not solvable on traditional computers
elements.2211.03212_fd2a0c45b63af63c1a45451aa115b: Following Moore's law, classical computers are getting increasingly dense and ever so slightly approaching the quantum domain which makes quantum computers the ideal candidate to replace classical ones as they fundamentally exploit the quantum phenomena
elements.2211.03212_a150a1dc00d349a815acc2d55449e: Quantum computers have also shown tremendous speed up in certain operations compared to classical ones
elements.2211.03212_4b605f79c0106b836cc1b9e64fa05: Google has shown this quantum supremacy in its seminal paper
elements.2211.03212_09c29ae69abba7ee0f8eceb9f3e7f: There are various ways to realize a quantum computer such as using superconducting circuits
elements.2211.03212_d0ab4e6e58af02ffa0be37d1d85f8: In all these approaches maintaining coherence between the states is a difficult task as the slightest of interaction with the surroundings will cause the system to lose its coherence and perform poorly
elements.2211.03212_07925603ef34a841eb0fa05923dbb: To overcome these difficulties a novel way of designing a universal quantum computer based on classical signals was introduced in
elements.2211.03212_10545a83776e2e833b6f611aefa50: A qubit may be represented as a pair of complex signals each corresponding to a binary state
elements.2211.03212_fb597a2ba1a8f2a498241a6a27a91: Superposition can then be considered as a scaled sum of these two complex signals and the orthogonality of these signals can be maintained by choosing the signals as in-phase and quadrature-phase signals of a Quadrature Amplitude Modulation (QAM) encoding scheme
elements.2211.03212_f44aa8e319efb6ba7f260893c0c07: A composite qubit system can then be constructed by utilizing more complex signals to represent the states
elements.2211.03212_caceab3c791a61598822c84e69b9b: This approach uses a classical, signal-based model to represent a multi-qubit quantum system along with all the gate operations and also allows us to apply a gate operation on a single qubit or multiple qubits, or all qubits at once
elements.2211.03212_77bf469b571441864422d1bab04bc: There are a lot of advantages to this approach such as no decoherence, no need to operate the device close to absolute zero, and less complexity of the circuit
elements.2211.03212_1371f6ea7e09f680e2d9d7f3f7b54: Another non-trivial advantage of using an emulator is using this to solve problems in
elements.2211.03212_ae5af09a56fe42727d29b68d55803: as suggested by Abrams and Lloyd by adding non-linearity to the operators
elements.2211.03212_d60f96dcacee5b9a776ea43af7282: Unfortunately, quantum mechanics has strictly linear time evolution but an emulation device operating on signals is not limited by that
elements.2211.03212_f8902c57ea6a3e05f5b6c6ef74aa8: Even though this is a very promising approach that exhibits inherent parallelism as much as any other quantum computer and can take advantage of quantum entanglement, this approach is not scalable
elements.2211.03212_f04b2aebf346a5c7f81830db831e7: To address the issue of scalability in this model, another approach was introduced
elements.2211.03212_993a71fadc384e614a3c3cd661674: whereby repeating the qubit complex signal either in the spatial domain or temporal domain increases the total number of qubits in the system
elements.2211.03212_e846d9da9ce24946580b47f02ac7c: This solves the issue of scalability to some extent but the size of the circuit still grows exponentially with the number of qubits which makes this device to be used only in a compact form with limited qubits
elements.2211.03212_85ed30a749f20442d2d7f8ec476cb: This can be used as a co-processor performing accelerated tasks besides a digital processor similar to the FPGA-based accelerators used in deep learning
elements.2211.03212_5b3a85f2f9cd321091b3e258f30cb: In this work, we would like to design an analog quantum emulation device (AQED) that uses the repetition of qubit signals in the spatial domain to increase the number of qubits
elements.2211.03212_85ee309dad1267cf6ec6557fe9adc: qubit system emulating two of the most important quantum algorithms: Grover's Search Algorithm (GSA)
